# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: high-throughput-screening
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:high-throughput-screening/assay] An **assay** is an investigative (analytic) procedure in laboratory medicine, mining, pharmacology, environmental biology and molecular biology for qualitatively assessing or quantitatively measuring the presence, amount, or functional activity of a target entity.
[src:high-throughput-screening/assay] The measured entity is often called the **analyte**, the **measurand**, or the **target** of the assay.
[src:high-throughput-screening/assay] The analyte can be a drug, biochemical substance, chemical element or compound, or cell in an organism or organic sample.
[src:high-throughput-screening/assay] An assay usually aims to measure an analyte's intensive property and express it in the relevant measurement unit (e.g. molarity, density, functional activity in enzyme international units, degree of effect in comparison to a standard, etc.).
[src:high-throughput-screening/assay] If the assay involves exogenous reactants (the reagents), then their quantities are kept fixed (or in excess) so that the quantity and quality of the target are the only limiting factors.
[src:high-throughput-screening/assay] The difference in the assay outcome is used to deduce the unknown quality or quantity of the target in question.
[src:high-throughput-screening/assay] Some assays (e.g., biochemical assays) may be similar to chemical analysis and titration.
[src:high-throughput-screening/assay] However, assays typically involve biological material or phenomena that are intrinsically more complex in composition or behavior, or both.
[src:high-throughput-screening/assay] Thus, reading of an assay may be noisy and involve greater difficulties in interpretation than an accurate chemical titration.
[src:high-throughput-screening/assay] On the other hand, older generation qualitative assays, especially bioassays, may be much more gross and less quantitative (e.g., counting death or dysfunction of an organism or cells in a population, or some descriptive change in some body part of a group of animals).
[src:high-throughput-screening/assay] Assays have become a routine part of modern medical, environmental, pharmaceutical, and forensic technology.
[src:high-throughput-screening/assay] Other businesses may also employ them at the industrial, curbside, or field levels.
[src:high-throughput-screening/assay] Assays in high commercial demand have been well investigated in research and development sectors of professional industries.
[src:high-throughput-screening/assay] They have also undergone generations of development and sophistication.
[src:high-throughput-screening/assay] In some cases, they are protected by intellectual property regulations such as patents granted for inventions.
[src:high-throughput-screening/assay] Analytes are generally tested in high-throughput autoanalyzers, and the results are verified and automatically returned to ordering service providers and end-users.
[src:high-throughput-screening/assay] These are made possible through the use of an advanced laboratory informatics system that interfaces with multiple computer terminals with end-users, central servers, the physical autoanalyzer instruments, and other automata.
[src:high-throughput-screening/assay] According to Etymology Online, the verb *assay* means "to try, endeavor, strive, test the quality of"; from Anglo-French *assaier*, from *assai* (noun), from Old French *essai*, "trial".
[src:high-throughput-screening/assay] Thus the noun *assay* means "trial, test of quality, test of character" (from mid-14th century), from Anglo-French *assai*; and its meaning "analysis" is from the late 14th century.
[src:high-throughput-screening/assay] For assay of currency coins this literally meant analysis of the purity of the gold or silver (or whatever the precious component) that represented the true value of the coin.
[src:high-throughput-screening/assay] An assay (analysis) is never an isolated process, as it must be accompanied with pre- and post-analytic procedures.
[src:high-throughput-screening/assay] Both the communication order (the request to perform an assay plus related information) *and* the handling of the specimen itself (the collecting, documenting, transporting, and processing done before beginning the assay) are pre-analytic steps.
[src:high-throughput-screening/assay] Similarly, after the assay is completed the results must be documented, verified and communicated—the post-analytic steps.
[src:high-throughput-screening/assay] As with any multi-step information handling and transmission system, the variation and errors in reporting final results entail not only those intrinsic to the assay itself but also those occurring in the pre-analytic and post-analytic procedures.
[src:high-throughput-screening/assay] **Target-specific discrimination/identification principle**: to discriminate from background (noise) of similar components and specifically identify a particular target component ("analyte") in a biological material by its specific attributes.
[src:high-throughput-screening/assay] (e.g. in a PCR assay a specific oligonucleotide primer identifies the target by base pairing based on the specific nucleotide sequence unique to the target).
[src:high-throughput-screening/assay] Sometimes the concentration of the analyte is too large and in that case the assay may involve sample dilution or some sort of signal diminution system which is a negative amplification.
[src:high-throughput-screening/assay] **Signal detection (and interpretation) system**: A system of deciphering the amplified signal into an interpretable output that can be quantitative or qualitative.
[src:high-throughput-screening/assay] It can be visual or manual very crude methods or can be very sophisticated electronic digital or analog detectors.
[src:high-throughput-screening/assay] **Signal enhancement and noise filtering** may be done at any or all of the steps above.
[src:high-throughput-screening/assay] These may simply be in the form of a narrow band-pass optical filter, or a blocking reagent in a binding reaction that prevents nonspecific binding or a quenching reagent in a fluorescence detection system that prevents "autofluorescence" of background objects.
[src:high-throughput-screening/assay] A **kinetic assay**, in which measurements are performed multiple times over a fixed time interval.
[src:high-throughput-screening/assay] Kinetic assay results may be visualized numerically (for example, as a slope parameter representing the rate of signal change over time), or graphically (for example, as a plot of the signal measured at each time point).
[src:high-throughput-screening/assay] For kinetic assays, both the magnitude and shape of the measured response over time provide important information.
[src:high-throughput-screening/assay] A **high throughput assay** can be either an endpoint or a kinetic assay usually done on an automated platform in 96-, 384- or 1536-well microplate formats (**High Throughput Screening**).
[src:high-throughput-screening/assay] Such assays are able to test large number of compounds or analytes or make functional biological readouts in response to a stimuli and/or compounds being tested.
[src:high-throughput-screening/assay] Multiplex assays are used to simultaneously measure the presence, concentration, activity, or quality of multiple analytes in a single test.
[src:high-throughput-screening/assay] The advent of *multiplexing* enabled rapid, efficient sample testing in many fields, including immunology, cytochemistry, genetics/genomics, pharmacokinetics, and toxicology.
[src:high-throughput-screening/assay] **Semi-quantitative assays**, i.e. assays that give the read-out in an approximate fashion rather than an exact number for the quantity of the substance.
[src:high-throughput-screening/assay] Generally they have a few more gradations than just two outcomes, positive or negative, e.g. scoring on a scale of 1+ to 4+ as used for blood grouping tests based on RBC agglutination in response to grouping reagents (antibody against blood group antigens).
[src:high-throughput-screening/assay] **Quantitative assays**, i.e. assays that give accurate and exact numeric quantitative measure of the amount of a substance in a sample.
[src:high-throughput-screening/assay] An example of such an assay used in coagulation testing laboratories for the most common inherited bleeding disease - Von Willebrand disease is VWF antigen assay where the amount of VWF present in a blood sample is measured by an immunoassay.
[src:high-throughput-screening/assay] **Functional assays**, i.e. an assay that tries to quantify functioning of an active substance rather than just its quantity.
[src:high-throughput-screening/assay] A similar assay but used for a different purpose is called Ristocetin Induced Platelet Aggregation or RIPA, which tests response of endogenous live platelets from a patient in response to Ristocetin (exogenous) & VWF (usually endogenous).
[src:high-throughput-screening/assay] *ex vivo* part of an organ (e.g. a segment of an intestine).
[src:high-throughput-screening/assay] **Ligand binding assay** when a ligand (usually a small molecule) binds a receptor (usually a large protein).
[src:high-throughput-screening/assay] **Immunoassay** when the response is an antigen antibody binding type reaction.
[src:high-throughput-screening/assay] Light detection systems that may use amplification e.g. by a photodiode or a photomultiplier tube or a cooled charge-coupled device.
[src:high-throughput-screening/assay] **Combination Methods** Assays may utilize a combination of the above and other amplification methods to improve sensitivity. e.g.
[src:high-throughput-screening/assay] Enzyme-linked immunoassay or EIA, enzyme linked immunosorbent assay.
[src:high-throughput-screening/assay] **Photometry** / **spectrophotometry** When the absorbance of a specific wavelength of light while passing through a fixed path-length through a cuvette of liquid test sample is measured and the absorbance is compared with a blank and standards with graded amounts of the target compound.
[src:high-throughput-screening/assay] If the emitted light is of a specific visible wavelength it may be called **colorimetry**, or it may involve specific wavelength of light e.g. by use of laser and emission of fluorescent signals of another specific wavelength which is detected via very specific wavelength optical filters.
[src:high-throughput-screening/assay] **Transmittance** of light may be used to measure e.g. clearing of opacity of a liquid created by suspended particles due to decrease in number of clumps during a platelet agglutination reaction.
[src:high-throughput-screening/assay] **Turbidimetry** when the opacity of straight-transmitted light passing through a liquid sample is measured by detectors placed straight across the light source.
[src:high-throughput-screening/assay] **Nephelometry** where a measurement of the amount of light scattering that occurs when a beam of light is passed through the solution is used to determine size and/or concentration and/or size distribution of particles in the sample.
[src:high-throughput-screening/assay] **Reflectometry** When color of light reflected from a (usually dry) sample or reactant is assessed e.g. the automated readings of the strip urine dipstick assays.
[src:high-throughput-screening/assay] Electric detection e.g. involving amperometry, Voltammetry, coulometry may be used directly or indirectly for many types of quantitative measurements.
[src:high-throughput-screening/assay] A cell-counting assay may determine the number of living cells, the number of dead cells, or the ratio of one cell type to another, such as enumerating and typing red versus different types of white blood cells.
[src:high-throughput-screening/assay] This is measured by different physical methods (light transmission, electric current change).
[src:high-throughput-screening/assay] But other methods use biochemical probing cell structure or physiology (stains).
[src:high-throughput-screening/assay] Another application is to monitor cell culture (assays of cell proliferation or cytotoxicity).
[src:high-throughput-screening/assay] A cytotoxicity assay measures how toxic a chemical compound is to cells.
[src:high-throughput-screening/assay] Many cell assays have been developed to assess specific parameters or response of cells (biomarkers, cell physiology).
[src:high-throughput-screening/assay] The HPCE-based viral titer assay uses a proprietary, high-performance capillary electrophoresis system to determine baculovirus titer.
[src:high-throughput-screening/assay] The Trofile assay is used to determine HIV tropism.
[src:high-throughput-screening/assay] The viral plaque assay is to calculate the number of viruses present in a sample.
[src:high-throughput-screening/assay] In this technique the number of viral plaques formed by a viral inoculum is counted, from which the actual virus concentration can be determined.
[src:high-throughput-screening/assay] A wide range of cellular secretions (say, a specific antibody or cytokine) can be detected using the ELISA technique.
[src:high-throughput-screening/assay] The number of cells which secrete those particular substances can be determined using a related technique, the ELISPOT assay.
[src:high-throughput-screening/assay] When multiple assays measure the same target their results and utility may or may not be comparable depending on the natures of the assay and their methodology, reliability etc.
[src:high-throughput-screening/assay] Bioactivity databases correlate structures or other chemical information to bioactivity results taken from bioassays in literature, patents, and screening programs.
[src:high-throughput-screening/assay] Protocol databases correlate results from bioassays to their metadata about experimental conditions and protocol designs.
[src:high-throughput-screening/high-throughput-screening] The key labware or testing vessel of HTS is the microtiter plate, which is a small container, usually disposable and made of plastic, that features a grid of small, open divots called *wells*.
[src:high-throughput-screening/high-throughput-screening] These are all multiples of 96, reflecting the original 96-well microplate with spaced wells of 8 x 12 with 9 mm spacing.
[src:high-throughput-screening/high-throughput-screening] Most of the wells contain test items, depending on the nature of the experiment.
[src:high-throughput-screening/high-throughput-screening] These could be different chemical compounds dissolved e.g. in an aqueous solution of dimethyl sulfoxide (DMSO).
[src:high-throughput-screening/high-throughput-screening] The wells could also contain cells or enzymes of some type.
[src:high-throughput-screening/high-throughput-screening] A screening facility typically holds a library of *stock plates*, whose contents are carefully catalogued, and each of which may have been created by the lab or obtained from a commercial source.
[src:high-throughput-screening/high-throughput-screening] These stock plates themselves are not directly used in experiments; instead, separate *assay plates* are created as needed.
[src:high-throughput-screening/high-throughput-screening] An assay plate is simply a copy of a stock plate, created by pipetting a small amount of liquid (often measured in nanoliters) from the wells of a stock plate to the corresponding wells of a completely empty plate.
[src:high-throughput-screening/high-throughput-screening] To prepare for an assay, the researcher fills each well of the plate with some biological entity that they wish to conduct the experiment upon, such as a protein, cells, or an animal embryo.
[src:high-throughput-screening/high-throughput-screening] After some incubation time has passed to allow the biological matter to absorb, bind to, or otherwise react (or fail to react) with the compounds in the wells, measurements are taken across all the plate's wells, either manually or by a machine.
[src:high-throughput-screening/high-throughput-screening] Manual measurements are often necessary when the researcher is using microscopy to (for example) seek changes or defects in embryonic development caused by the wells' compounds, looking for effects that a computer could not easily determine by itself.
[src:high-throughput-screening/high-throughput-screening] Otherwise, a specialized automated analysis machine can run a number of experiments on the wells (such as shining polarized light on them and measuring reflectivity, which can be an indication of protein binding).
[src:high-throughput-screening/high-throughput-screening] In this case, the machine outputs the result of each experiment as a grid of numeric values, with each number mapping to the value obtained from a single well.
[src:high-throughput-screening/high-throughput-screening] A high-capacity analysis machine can measure dozens of plates in the space of a few minutes like this, generating thousands of experimental datapoints very quickly.
[src:high-throughput-screening/high-throughput-screening] Automation is an essential element in HTS's usefulness.
[src:high-throughput-screening/high-throughput-screening] Typically, an integrated robot system consisting of one or more robots transports assay-microplates from station to station for sample and reagent addition, mixing, incubation, and finally readout or detection.
[src:high-throughput-screening/high-throughput-screening] An HTS system can usually prepare, incubate, and analyze many plates simultaneously, further speeding the data-collection process.
[src:high-throughput-screening/high-throughput-screening] HTS robots that can test up to 100,000 compounds per day currently exist.
[src:high-throughput-screening/high-throughput-screening] Automatic colony pickers pick thousands of microbial colonies for high throughput genetic screening.
[src:high-throughput-screening/high-throughput-screening] The term uHTS or *ultra-high-throughput screening* refers (circa 2008) to screening in excess of 100,000 compounds per day.
[src:high-throughput-screening/high-throughput-screening] With the ability of rapid screening of diverse compounds (such as small molecules or siRNAs) to identify active compounds, HTS has led to an explosion in the rate of data generated in recent years .
[src:high-throughput-screening/high-throughput-screening] Consequently, one of the most fundamental challenges in HTS experiments is to glean biochemical significance from mounds of data, which relies on the development and adoption of appropriate experimental designs and analytic methods for both quality control and hit selection .
[src:high-throughput-screening/high-throughput-screening] High-quality HTS assays are critical in HTS experiments.
[src:high-throughput-screening/high-throughput-screening] The development of high-quality HTS assays requires the integration of both experimental and computational approaches for quality control (QC).
[src:high-throughput-screening/high-throughput-screening] Three important means of QC are (i) good plate design, (ii) the selection of effective positive and negative chemical/biological controls, and (iii) the development of effective QC metrics to measure the degree of differentiation so that assays with inferior data quality can be identified.
[src:high-throughput-screening/high-throughput-screening] A good plate design helps to identify systematic errors (especially those linked with well position) and determine what normalization should be used to remove/reduce the impact of systematic errors on both QC and hit selection.
[src:high-throughput-screening/high-throughput-screening] Effective analytic QC methods serve as a gatekeeper for excellent quality assays.
[src:high-throughput-screening/high-throughput-screening] In a typical HTS experiment, a clear distinction between a positive control and a negative reference such as a negative control is an index for good quality.
[src:high-throughput-screening/high-throughput-screening] Many quality-assessment measures have been proposed to measure the degree of differentiation between a positive control and a negative reference.
[src:high-throughput-screening/high-throughput-screening] Signal-to-background ratio, signal-to-noise ratio, signal window, assay variability ratio, and Z-factor have been adopted to evaluate data quality.
[src:high-throughput-screening/high-throughput-screening] Strictly standardized mean difference (SSMD) has recently been proposed for assessing data quality in HTS assays.
[src:high-throughput-screening/high-throughput-screening] A compound with a desired size of effects in an HTS is called a hit.
[src:high-throughput-screening/high-throughput-screening] The process of selecting hits is called hit selection.
[src:high-throughput-screening/high-throughput-screening] The analytic methods for hit selection in screens without replicates (usually in primary screens) differ from those with replicates (usually in confirmatory screens).
[src:high-throughput-screening/high-throughput-screening] For example, the z-score method is suitable for screens without replicates whereas the t-statistic is suitable for screens with replicates.
[src:high-throughput-screening/high-throughput-screening] The calculation of SSMD for screens without replicates also differs from that for screens with replicates .
[src:high-throughput-screening/high-throughput-screening] For hit selection in primary screens without replicates, the easily interpretable ones are average fold change, mean difference, percent inhibition, and percent activity.
[src:high-throughput-screening/high-throughput-screening] However, they do not capture data variability effectively.
[src:high-throughput-screening/high-throughput-screening] The z-score method or SSMD, which can capture data variability based on an assumption that every compound has the same variability as a negative reference in the screens.
[src:high-throughput-screening/high-throughput-screening] However, outliers are common in HTS experiments, and methods such as z-score are sensitive to outliers and can be problematic.
[src:high-throughput-screening/high-throughput-screening] As a consequence, robust methods such as the z*-score method, SSMD*, B-score method, and quantile-based method have been proposed and adopted for hit selection.
[src:high-throughput-screening/high-throughput-screening] In a screen with replicates, we can directly estimate variability for each compound; as a consequence, we should use SSMD or t-statistic that does not rely on the strong assumption that the z-score and z*-score rely on.
[src:high-throughput-screening/high-throughput-screening] One issue with the use of t-statistic and associated p-values is that they are affected by both sample size and effect size.
[src:high-throughput-screening/high-throughput-screening] They come from testing for no mean difference, and thus are not designed to measure the size of compound effects.
[src:high-throughput-screening/high-throughput-screening] For hit selection, the major interest is the size of effect in a tested compound.
[src:high-throughput-screening/high-throughput-screening] SSMD directly assesses the size of effects.
[src:high-throughput-screening/high-throughput-screening] SSMD has also been shown to be better than other commonly used effect sizes.
[src:high-throughput-screening/high-throughput-screening] The population value of SSMD is comparable across experiments and, thus, we can use the same cutoff for the population value of SSMD to measure the size of compound effects .
[src:high-throughput-screening/high-throughput-screening] Unique distributions of compounds across one or many plates can be employed either to increase the number of assays per plate or to reduce the variance of assay results, or both.
[src:high-throughput-screening/high-throughput-screening] The simplifying assumption made in this approach is that any N compounds in the same well will not typically interact with each other, or the assay target, in a manner that fundamentally changes the ability of the assay to detect true hits.
[src:high-throughput-screening/high-throughput-screening] For example, imagine a plate wherein compound A is in wells 1–2–3, compound B is in wells 2–3–4, and compound C is in wells 3–4–5.
[src:high-throughput-screening/high-throughput-screening] In an assay of this plate against a given target, a hit in wells 2, 3, and 4 would indicate that compound B is the most likely agent, while also providing three measurements of compound B's efficacy against the specified target.
[src:high-throughput-screening/high-throughput-screening] Commercial applications of this approach involve combinations in which no two compounds ever share more than one well, to reduce the (second-order) possibility of interference between pairs of compounds being screened.
[src:high-throughput-screening/high-throughput-screening] Automation and low volume assay formats were leveraged by scientists at the NIH Chemical Genomics Center (NCGC) to develop quantitative HTS (qHTS), a paradigm to pharmacologically profile large chemical libraries through the generation of full concentration-response relationships for each compound.
[src:high-throughput-screening/high-throughput-screening] With accompanying curve fitting and cheminformatics software qHTS data yields half maximal effective concentration (EC50), maximal response, Hill coefficient (nH) for the entire library enabling the assessment of nascent structure activity relationships (SAR).
[src:high-throughput-screening/high-throughput-screening] In March 2010, research was published demonstrating an HTS process allowing 1,000 times faster screening (100 million reactions in 10 hours) at 1-millionth the cost (using 10−7 times the reagent volume) than conventional techniques using drop-based microfluidics.
[src:high-throughput-screening/high-throughput-screening] Drops of fluid separated by oil replace microplate wells and allow analysis and hit sorting while reagents are flowing through channels.
[src:high-throughput-screening/high-throughput-screening] In 2010, researchers developed a silicon sheet of lenses that can be placed over microfluidic arrays to allow the fluorescence measurement of 64 different output channels simultaneously with a single camera.
[src:high-throughput-screening/high-throughput-screening] This process can analyze 200,000 drops per second.
[src:high-throughput-screening/high-throughput-screening] In 2013, researchers have disclosed an approach with small molecules from plants.
[src:high-throughput-screening/high-throughput-screening] In general, it is essential to provide high-quality proof-of-concept validations early in the drug discovery process.
[src:high-throughput-screening/high-throughput-screening] Here technologies that enable the identification of potent, selective, and bioavailable chemical probes are of crucial interest, even if the resulting compounds require further optimization for development into a pharmaceutical product.
[src:high-throughput-screening/high-throughput-screening] Nuclear receptor RORα, a protein that has been targeted for more than a decade to identify potent and bioavailable agonists, was used as an example of a very challenging drug target.
[src:high-throughput-screening/high-throughput-screening] Hits are confirmed at the screening step due to the bell-shaped curve.
[src:high-throughput-screening/high-throughput-screening] This method is very similar to the quantitative HTS method (screening and hit confirmation at the same time), except that using this approach greatly decreases the data point number and can screen easily more than 100.000 biological relevant compounds.
[src:high-throughput-screening/high-throughput-screening] Switching from an orbital shaker, which required milling times of 24 hours and at least 10 mg of drug compound to a ResonantAcoustic mixer, Merck reported reduced processing time to less than 2 hours on only 1-2 mg of drug compound per well.
[src:high-throughput-screening/high-throughput-screening] Merck also indicated the acoustic milling approach allows for the preparation of high dose nanosuspension formulations that could not be obtained using conventional milling equipment.
[src:high-throughput-screening/high-throughput-screening] Whereby traditional HTS drug discovery uses purified proteins or intact cells, recent development of the technology is associated with the use of intact living organisms, like the nematode *Caenorhabditis elegans* and zebrafish (*Danio rerio*).
[src:high-throughput-screening/high-throughput-screening] HTS is a relatively recent innovation, made feasible largely through modern advances in robotics and high-speed computer technology.
[src:high-throughput-screening/high-throughput-screening] It still takes a highly specialized and expensive screening lab to run an HTS operation, so in many cases a small- to moderate-size research institution will use the services of an existing HTS facility rather than set up one for itself.
[src:high-throughput-screening/high-throughput-screening] There is a trend in academia for universities to be their own drug discovery enterprise.
[src:high-throughput-screening/high-throughput-screening] These facilities, which normally are found only in industry, are now increasingly found at universities as well.
[src:high-throughput-screening/high-throughput-screening] UCLA, for example, features an open access HTS laboratory Molecular Screening Shared Resources (MSSR, UCLA), which can screen more than 100,000 compounds a day on a routine basis.
[src:high-throughput-screening/high-throughput-screening] The open access policy ensures that researchers from all over the world can take advantage of this facility without lengthy intellectual property negotiations.
[src:high-throughput-screening/high-throughput-screening] With a compound library of over 200,000 small molecules, the MSSR has one of the largest compound deck of all universities on the west coast.
[src:high-throughput-screening/high-throughput-screening] Parallel access to high-throughput small molecule screen and a genome wide screen enables researchers to perform target identification and validation for given disease or the mode of action determination on a small molecule.
[src:high-throughput-screening/high-throughput-screening] The most accurate results can be obtained by use of "arrayed" functional genomics libraries, i.e. each library contains a single construct such as a single siRNA or cDNA.
[src:high-throughput-screening/high-throughput-screening] Functional genomics is typically paired with high content screening using e.g. epifluorescent microscopy or laser scanning cytometry.
[src:high-throughput-screening/high-throughput-screening] The University of Illinois also has a facility for HTS, as does the University of Minnesota.
[src:high-throughput-screening/high-throughput-screening] The Life Sciences Institute at the University of Michigan houses the HTS facility in the Center for Chemical Genomics.
[src:high-throughput-screening/high-throughput-screening] Columbia University has an HTS shared resource facility with ~300,000 diverse small molecules and ~10,000 known bioactive compounds available for biochemical, cell-based and NGS-based screening.
[src:high-throughput-screening/high-throughput-screening] The Rockefeller University has an open-access HTS Resource Center HTSRC (The Rockefeller University, HTSRC), which offers a library of over 380,000 compounds.
[src:high-throughput-screening/high-throughput-screening] Northwestern University's High Throughput Analysis Laboratory supports target identification, validation, assay development, and compound screening.
[src:high-throughput-screening/high-throughput-screening] The non-profit Sanford Burnham Prebys Medical Discovery Institute also has a long-standing HTS facility in the Conrad Prebys Center for Chemical Genomics which was part of the MLPCN.
[src:high-throughput-screening/high-throughput-screening] The non-profit Scripps Research Molecular Screening Center (SRMSC) continues to serve academia across institutes post-MLPCN era.
[src:high-throughput-screening/high-throughput-screening] The SRMSC uHTS facility maintains one of the largest library collections in academia, presently at well-over 665,000 small molecule entities, and routinely screens the full collection or sub-libraries in support of multi-PI grant initiatives.
[src:high-throughput-screening/high-throughput-screening] In the United States, the National Institutes of Health or NIH has created a nationwide consortium of small-molecule screening centers to produce innovative chemical tools for use in biological research.
[src:high-throughput-screening/high-throughput-screening] The Molecular Libraries Probe Production Centers Network, or MLPCN, performs HTS on assays provided by the research community, against a large library of small molecules maintained in a central molecule repository.
[src:high-throughput-screening/high-throughput-screening] In addition, the NIH created the National Center for Advancing Translational Sciences or NCATS, housed in Shady Grove Maryland, that carries out small molecule and RNAi screens in collaboration with academic laboratories.
[src:high-throughput-screening/high-throughput-screening] Of note, the small molecule screening uses 1536 well plates, a capability rarely seen in academic screening laboratories that allows one to carry out quantitative HTS in which each compound is tested across four- to five-orders of magnitude of concentrations.
[src:high-throughput-screening/laboratory-automation] The most widely known application of laboratory automation technology is laboratory robotics.
[src:high-throughput-screening/laboratory-automation] The application of technology in today's laboratories is required to achieve timely progress and remain competitive.
[src:high-throughput-screening/laboratory-automation] Laboratories devoted to activities such as high-throughput screening, combinatorial chemistry, automated clinical and analytical testing, diagnostics, large-scale biorepositories, and many others, would not exist without advancements in laboratory automation.
[src:high-throughput-screening/laboratory-automation] Some universities offer entire programs that focus on lab technologies.
[src:high-throughput-screening/laboratory-automation] For example, Indiana University-Purdue University at Indianapolis offers a graduate program devoted to Laboratory Informatics.
[src:high-throughput-screening/laboratory-automation] Also, the Keck Graduate Institute in California offers a graduate degree with an emphasis on development of assays, instrumentation and data analysis tools required for clinical diagnostics, high-throughput screening, genotyping, microarray technologies, proteomics, imaging and other applications.
[src:high-throughput-screening/laboratory-automation] At least since 1875 there have been reports of automated devices for scientific investigation.
[src:high-throughput-screening/laboratory-automation] These first devices were mostly built by scientists themselves in order to solve problems in the laboratory.
[src:high-throughput-screening/laboratory-automation] After the second world war, companies started to provide automated equipment with greater and greater complexity.
[src:high-throughput-screening/laboratory-automation] Automation steadily spread in laboratories through the 20th century, but then a revolution took place: in the early 1980s, the first fully automated laboratory was opened by Dr.
[src:high-throughput-screening/laboratory-automation] Rod Markin at the University of Nebraska Medical Center created one of the world's first clinical automated laboratory management systems.
[src:high-throughput-screening/laboratory-automation] In the mid-1990s, he chaired a standards group called the Clinical Testing Automation Standards Steering Committee (CTASSC) of the American Association for Clinical Chemistry, which later evolved into an area committee of the Clinical and Laboratory Standards Institute.
[src:high-throughput-screening/laboratory-automation] In 2004, the National Institutes of Health (NIH) and more than 300 nationally recognized leaders in academia, industry, government, and the public completed the NIH Roadmap to accelerate medical discovery to improve health.
[src:high-throughput-screening/laboratory-automation] The NIH Roadmap clearly identifies technology development as a mission critical factor in the Molecular Libraries and Imaging Implementation Group (see the first theme – New Pathways to Discovery – at https://web.archive.org/web/20100611171315/http://nihroadmap.nih.gov/).
[src:high-throughput-screening/laboratory-automation] Sasaki laboratory and others of the kind, the multi-million dollar cost of such laboratories has prevented adoption by smaller groups.
[src:high-throughput-screening/laboratory-automation] This is all more difficult because devices made by different manufactures often cannot communicate with each other.
[src:high-throughput-screening/laboratory-automation] However, recent advances based on the use of scripting languages like Autoit have made possible the integration of equipment from different manufacturers.
[src:high-throughput-screening/laboratory-automation] Using this approach, many low-cost electronic devices, including open-source devices, become compatible with common laboratory instruments.
[src:high-throughput-screening/laboratory-automation] Some startups such as Emerald Cloud Lab and Strateos provide on-demand and remote laboratory access on a commercial scale.
[src:high-throughput-screening/laboratory-automation] A 2017 study indicates that these commercial-scale, fully integrated automated laboratories can improve reproducibility and transparency in basic biomedical experiments, and that over nine in ten biomedical papers use methods currently available through these groups.
[src:high-throughput-screening/laboratory-automation] A large obstacle to the implementation of automation in laboratories has been its high cost.
[src:high-throughput-screening/laboratory-automation] Many laboratory instruments are very expensive.
[src:high-throughput-screening/laboratory-automation] This is justifiable in many cases, as such equipment can perform very specific tasks employing cutting-edge technology.
[src:high-throughput-screening/laboratory-automation] However, there are devices employed in the laboratory that are not highly technological but still are very expensive.
[src:high-throughput-screening/laboratory-automation] This is the case of many automated devices, which perform tasks that could easily be done by simple and low-cost devices like simple robotic arms, universal (open-source) electronic modules, Lego Mindstorms, or 3D printers.
[src:high-throughput-screening/laboratory-automation] So far, using such low-cost devices together with laboratory equipment was considered to be very difficult.
[src:high-throughput-screening/laboratory-automation] However, it has been demonstrated that such low-cost devices can substitute without problems the standard machines used in laboratory.
[src:high-throughput-screening/laboratory-automation] It can be anticipated that more laboratories will take advantage of this new reality as low-cost automation is very attractive for laboratories.
[src:high-throughput-screening/laboratory-automation] A technology that enables the integration of any machine regardless of their brand is scripting, more specifically, scripting involving the control of mouse clicks and keyboard entries, like AutoIt.
[src:high-throughput-screening/laboratory-automation] By timing clicks and keyboard inputs, different software interfaces controlling different devices can be perfectly synchronized.
[src:high-throughput-screening/microplate] A **microplate**, also known as a **microtiter plate**, **microwell plate** or **multiwell**, is a flat plate with multiple "wells" used as small test tubes.
[src:high-throughput-screening/microplate] The microplate has become a standard tool in analytical research and clinical diagnostic testing laboratories.
[src:high-throughput-screening/microplate] A very common usage is in the enzyme-linked immunosorbent assay (ELISA), the basis of most modern medical diagnostic testing in humans and animals.
[src:high-throughput-screening/microplate] A microplate typically has 6, 12, 24, 48, 96, 384 or 1536 sample wells arranged in a 2:3 rectangular matrix.
[src:high-throughput-screening/microplate] Some microplates have been manufactured with 3456 or 9600 wells, and an "array tape" product has been developed that provides a continuous strip of microplates embossed on a flexible plastic tape.
[src:high-throughput-screening/microplate] Each well of a microplate typically holds somewhere between tens of nanolitres to several millilitres of liquid.
[src:high-throughput-screening/microplate] They can also be used to store dry powder or as racks to support glass tube inserts.
[src:high-throughput-screening/microplate] For compound storage applications, square wells with close fitting silicone cap-mats are preferred.
[src:high-throughput-screening/microplate] Microplates can be stored at low temperatures for long periods, may be heated to increase the rate of solvent evaporation from their wells and can even be heat-sealed with foil or clear film.
[src:high-throughput-screening/microplate] The enormous growth in studies of whole live cells has led to an entirely new range of microplate products which are "tissue culture treated" especially for this work.
[src:high-throughput-screening/microplate] The surfaces of these products are modified using an oxygen plasma discharge to make their surfaces more hydrophilic so that it becomes easier for adherent cells to grow on the surface which would otherwise be strongly hydrophobic.
[src:high-throughput-screening/microplate] A number of companies have developed robots to specifically handle microplates.
[src:high-throughput-screening/microplate] Instrument companies have designed plate readers which can detect specific biological, chemical or physical events in samples stored in these plates.
[src:high-throughput-screening/microplate] A specialized plate reader has also been developed which can perform quality control of microplate well contents, capable of identifying empty wells, filled wells and precipitate.
[src:high-throughput-screening/microplate] The most common manufacturing process is injection molding, using materials such as polystyrene, polypropylene and cyclo-olefin for different temperature and chemical resistance needs.
[src:high-throughput-screening/microplate] Glass is also a possible material, and vacuum forming can be used with many other plastics such as polycarbonate.
[src:high-throughput-screening/microplate] Composite microplates, including filter bottom plates, solid phase extraction (SPE) plates, and even some advanced PCR plate designs, use multiple components and/or materials which are moulded separately and later assembled into a finished product.
[src:high-throughput-screening/microplate] ELISA plates may now be assembled from twelve separate strips of eight wells, making it easier to only partially use a plate.
[src:high-throughput-screening/microplate] There are also less common 192- and 768-well plates.
[src:high-throughput-screening/microplate] An attempt at standardizing microplates was made by the Society for Biomolecular Sciences with the ANSI-Standards (ANSI/SBS 1-2004, ANSI/SBS 2-2004, ANSI/SBS 3-2004, ANSI/SBS 4-2004).
[src:high-throughput-screening/microplate] These standards have been updated to and are now known as the ANSI SLAS standards.
[src:high-throughput-screening/microplate] The ANSI SLAS microplate standards define a footprint, and a bottom flange geometry.
[src:high-throughput-screening/microplate] The well position is also standardized, but only for 96- , 384-, and 1536-well plates.
[src:high-throughput-screening/microplate] 96-well plates have a 9 mm well-to-well spacing, 384-wells a 4.5 mm spacing, and 1536-wells a 2.25 mm spacing.
[src:high-throughput-screening/microplate] A notable characteristic is that the well array is symmetrical when the plate is rotated 180˚ around its Z-axis (height axis).
[src:high-throughput-screening/microplate] Therefore, scientific instruments which use microplates, can accept the plate in one of two rotated orientations - either "correct" or 180˚ rotated.
[src:high-throughput-screening/microplate] Other variants like 24-well plates, are not considered in the standard, but there is a *de facto* standard to implement to 24-wells by apply the same scaling factor as the 384- to 96-well transition, i.e.
[src:high-throughput-screening/microplate] Notably, the shape and diameter of the well is not standardized, and has several proprietary implementations.
[src:high-throughput-screening/microplate] This causes difficulties with accessory cross-compatibility such as with microplate cap mats.
[src:high-throughput-screening/microplate] The most recent addition to the ANSI SLAS microplate standards was the inclusion of a well bottom standard.
[src:high-throughput-screening/microplate] The standard however specifies definitions and test methods only, for the "Microplate Well Bottom Elevation (WBE)", "Well Bottom Elevation Variation (WBEV)", and "Intra-Well Bottom Elevation Variation (IWBEV)", but it does not state a preferred value or limits for those dimensional definitions.
[src:high-throughput-screening/microplate] Therefore all well bottom heights are currently proprietary implementations without a clear *de facto* standard.
[src:high-throughput-screening/microplate] This lack of standardization can cause difficulties with applications such as automated autosampler needle injection.
[src:high-throughput-screening/microplate] The height of a standard microplate is also defined, however this is sometimes not followed by manufacturers, even if they follow the footprint and flange standards.
[src:high-throughput-screening/microplate] There are also deep well microplates sometimes called "blocks".
[src:high-throughput-screening/microplate] Unlike plates of normal height, the ANSI SLAS 2-2004 height standard, does not define a standard height for deep well plates (blocks).
[src:high-throughput-screening/microplate] Deepwell plates do typically follow a *de facto* standard height of 44 mm.
[src:high-throughput-screening/microplate] Reservoir plates are also commercially available.
[src:high-throughput-screening/microplate] Reservoir plates have columns of wells (as in 96-well, 24-well, etc. plates) that are fused into single wells, so that they provide additional volume for multichannel pipettes.
[src:high-throughput-screening/microplate] Like deepwell plates or blocks, they often follow a *de facto* standard height of 44 mm.
[src:high-throughput-screening/microplate] Microplates used for PCR are designed to have a notably thinner wall thickness than standard ANSI/SLAS microplates (to allow for better thermal conduction), and to come in a few different "skirt" types: full-skirt, half-skirt or semi-skirted, and unskirted or no-skirted.
[src:high-throughput-screening/microplate] The skirt is analogous to the footprint & flange of the ANSI/SLAS standards, so while most full-skirt PCR microplates may be ANSI/SLAS compliant, other deviations such as semi-skirted or others, are not compliant ANSI/SLAS standards.
[src:high-throughput-screening/microplate] The earliest microplate was created in 1951 by a Hungarian, Dr.
[src:high-throughput-screening/microplate] Gyula Takátsy, who machined six rows of 12 "wells" in Lucite.
[src:high-throughput-screening/microplate] John Louis Sever modified the Hungarian design into a 96-well plate, which he published in 1962.
[src:high-throughput-screening/microplate] However, common usage of the microplate began in the late 1980s when John Liner introduced a molded version.
[src:high-throughput-screening/microplate] By 1990 there were more than 15 companies producing a wide range of microplates with different features.
[src:high-throughput-screening/microplate] It was estimated that 125 million microplates were used in 2000 alone.
[src:high-throughput-screening/microplate] The word "Microtiter" is a registered trademark of Thermo Electron OY (U.S.
[src:high-throughput-screening/microplate] Other trade names for microplates include Viewplate and Unifilter (introduced in the early 1990s by Polyfiltronics and sold by Packard Instrument, which is now part of PerkinElmer).
[src:high-throughput-screening/microplate] In 1996, the Society for Biomolecular Screening (SBS), later known as Society for Biomolecular Sciences, began an initiative to create a standard definition of a microplate.
[src:high-throughput-screening/microplate] A series of standards was proposed in 2003 and published by the American National Standards Institute (ANSI) on behalf of the SBS.
[src:high-throughput-screening/microplate] In 2010, the Society for Biomolecular Sciences merged with the Association for Laboratory Automation (ALA) to form a new organisation, the Society for Laboratory Automation and Screening (SLAS).
[src:high-throughput-screening/microplate] Henceforth, the microplate standards are known as ANSI SLAS standards.
[src:high-throughput-screening/reporter-gene] Reporter genes are molecular tools widely used in molecular biology, genetics, and biotechnology to study gene function, expression patterns, and regulatory mechanisms.
[src:high-throughput-screening/reporter-gene] These genes encode proteins that produce easily detectable signals, such as fluorescence, luminescence, or enzymatic activity, allowing researchers to monitor cellular processes in real-time.
[src:high-throughput-screening/reporter-gene] Reporter genes are often fused to regulatory sequences of genes of interest, enabling scientists to analyze promoter activity, transcriptional regulation, and signal transduction pathways.
[src:high-throughput-screening/reporter-gene] Common **reporter gene** systems include green fluorescent protein (GFP), β-galactosidase (lacZ), luciferase, and chloramphenicol acetyltransferase (CAT), each offering distinct advantages depending on the experimental application.
[src:high-throughput-screening/reporter-gene] Their versatility makes reporter genes invaluable in fields such as drug discovery, gene therapy, and synthetic biology.
[src:high-throughput-screening/reporter-gene] To introduce a reporter gene into an organism, scientists place the reporter gene and the gene of interest in the same DNA construct to be inserted into the cell or organism.
[src:high-throughput-screening/reporter-gene] For bacteria or prokaryotic cells in culture, this is usually in the form of a circular DNA molecule called a plasmid.
[src:high-throughput-screening/reporter-gene] For viruses, this is known as a viral vector.
[src:high-throughput-screening/reporter-gene] It is important to use a reporter gene that is not natively expressed in the cell or organism under study, since the expression of the reporter is being used as a marker for successful uptake of the gene of interest.
[src:high-throughput-screening/reporter-gene] Commonly used reporter genes that induce visually identifiable characteristics usually involve fluorescent and luminescent proteins.
[src:high-throughput-screening/reporter-gene] Examples include the gene that encodes jellyfish green fluorescent protein (GFP), which causes cells that express it to glow green under blue or ultraviolet light, the enzyme luciferase, which catalyzes a reaction with luciferin to produce light, and the red fluorescent protein from the gene dsRed.
[src:high-throughput-screening/reporter-gene] The GUS gene has been commonly used in plants, but luciferase and GFP are becoming more common.
[src:high-throughput-screening/reporter-gene] A common reporter in bacteria is the *E. coli* *lacZ* gene, which encodes the protein beta-galactosidase.
[src:high-throughput-screening/reporter-gene] This enzyme causes bacteria expressing the gene to appear blue when grown on a medium that contains the substrate analog X-gal.
[src:high-throughput-screening/reporter-gene] An example of a selectable marker, which is also a reporter in bacteria, is the chloramphenicol acetyltransferase (CAT) gene, which confers resistance to the antibiotic chloramphenicol.
[src:high-throughput-screening/reporter-gene] Many methods of transfection and transformation – two ways of expressing a foreign or modified gene in an organism – are effective in only a small percentage of a population subjected to the techniques.
[src:high-throughput-screening/reporter-gene] Thus, a method for identifying those few successful gene uptake events is necessary.
[src:high-throughput-screening/reporter-gene] Reporter genes used in this way are normally expressed under their own promoter (DNA regions that initiates gene transcription) independent from that of the introduced gene of interest; the reporter gene can be expressed constitutively ("always on") or inducibly.
[src:high-throughput-screening/reporter-gene] This independence is advantageous when the gene of interest is expressed under specific or hard-to-access conditions.
[src:high-throughput-screening/reporter-gene] In the case of selectable-marker reporters such as *CAT*, the transfected population can be grown on a chloramphenicol-containing substrate.
[src:high-throughput-screening/reporter-gene] Only cells with the *CAT* gene survive, confirming successful transformation.
[src:high-throughput-screening/reporter-gene] Reporter genes can be used to assay for the expression of a gene of interest that is normally difficult to quantitatively assay.
[src:high-throughput-screening/reporter-gene] Reporter genes can produce a protein that has little obvious or immediate effect on the cell culture or organism.
[src:high-throughput-screening/reporter-gene] They are ideally not present in the native genome to be able to isolate reporter gene expression as a result of the gene of interest's expression.
[src:high-throughput-screening/reporter-gene] To activate reporter genes, they can be expressed constitutively, where they are directly attached to the gene of interest to create a gene fusion.
[src:high-throughput-screening/reporter-gene] This method is an example of using *cis*-acting elements where the two genes are under the same promoter elements and are transcribed into a single messenger RNA molecule.
[src:high-throughput-screening/reporter-gene] The mRNA is then translated into protein.
[src:high-throughput-screening/reporter-gene] It is important that both proteins be able to properly fold into their active conformations and interact with their substrates despite being fused.
[src:high-throughput-screening/reporter-gene] In building the DNA construct, a segment of DNA coding for a flexible polypeptide linker region is usually included so that the reporter and the gene product will only minimally interfere with one another.
[src:high-throughput-screening/reporter-gene] Reporter genes can also be expressed by induction during growth.
[src:high-throughput-screening/reporter-gene] In these cases, *trans*-acting elements, such as transcription factors are used to express the reporter gene.
[src:high-throughput-screening/reporter-gene] Reporter gene assay have been increasingly used in high throughput screening (HTS) to identify small molecule inhibitors and activators of protein targets and pathways for drug discovery and chemical biology.
[src:high-throughput-screening/reporter-gene] Because the reporter enzymes themselves (e.g. firefly luciferase) can be direct targets of small molecules and confound the interpretation of HTS data, novel coincidence reporter designs incorporating artifact suppression have been developed.
[src:high-throughput-screening/reporter-gene] Reporter genes can be used to assay for the activity of a particular promoter in a cell or organism.
[src:high-throughput-screening/reporter-gene] In this case there is no separate "gene of interest"; the reporter gene is simply placed under the control of the target promoter and the reporter gene product's activity is quantitatively measured.
[src:high-throughput-screening/reporter-gene] The results are normally reported relative to the activity under a "consensus" promoter known to induce strong gene expression.
[src:high-throughput-screening/reporter-gene] While reporter gene technology has become an essential component of molecular biology, its application still has limitations.
[src:high-throughput-screening/reporter-gene] One primary concern is the influence of genomic context on reporter expression.
[src:high-throughput-screening/reporter-gene] Reporter genes integrated into the genome can be subject to position-effect variegation, where the surrounding chromatin structure influences transcriptional activity.
[src:high-throughput-screening/reporter-gene] This can lead to inconsistent expression and complicate the interpretation of results, especially in stable cell lines and transgenic organisms.
[src:high-throughput-screening/reporter-gene] Additionally, reporter expression may not always accurately reflect the activity of the endogenous gene of interest due to differences in post-transcriptional regulation, mRNA stability, or translational efficiency.
[src:high-throughput-screening/reporter-gene] Another common limitation is the cellular burden that reporter expression may impose.
[src:high-throughput-screening/reporter-gene] High levels of reporter protein production, such as fluorescent proteins or luciferases, can divert cellular resources, potentially impacting normal metabolism or physiology.
[src:high-throughput-screening/reporter-gene] This is particularly problematic in sensitive systems like stem cells or primary cell cultures, where even subtle changes in metabolism can influence cell behavior.
[src:high-throughput-screening/reporter-gene] Additionally, some reporter systems, like luciferase assays, require the addition of exogenous substrates (e.g., luciferin), adds complexity and may reduce reproducibility, particularly in live animal models where substrate availability can vary.
[src:high-throughput-screening/reporter-gene] To address these challenges, several innovations have improved the reliability and flexibility of reporter gene technologies.
[src:high-throughput-screening/reporter-gene] One advancement involves the use of the 2A peptide, which allows the co-expression of multiple proteins from a single transcript without requiring a direct fusion.
[src:high-throughput-screening/reporter-gene] This approach enables the simultaneous expression of a gene of interest and a reporter while preserving the function of both.
[src:high-throughput-screening/reporter-gene] Additionally, split-reporter systems, which produce a functional signal only when two proteins of interest interact, have become widely used in studies of protein–protein interactions due to their low background activity and high specificity.
[src:high-throughput-screening/reporter-gene] Tracking expression has allowed for multiple investigations into the progression of diseased cells.
[src:high-throughput-screening/reporter-gene] Reporter genes have shown to provide critical insight into genes upregulated in cancer regulatory pathways as well as the identification into oncogenes and tumor suppressor genes.
[src:high-throughput-screening/reporter-gene] These have been used for further research into the development of therapeutics to stop further disease progression and metastasis.
[src:high-throughput-screening/reporter-gene] Gene therapy has also been tracked through the use of reporter genes.
[src:high-throughput-screening/reporter-gene] This allows for the monitoring of gene therapy vectors to see if they are achieving intended results as well as to monitor patient safety for short and long term periods.
[src:high-throughput-screening/reporter-gene] Therapeutics developed have benefited from the use of reporter genres such as a dual-reporter system developed for CRISPR/Cas9 models to monitor progression and success and benefits of being gene editing tools.
[src:high-throughput-screening/reporter-gene] The most commonly used application used for reporter genes has been for the identification of cis and trans acting elements.
[src:high-throughput-screening/reporter-gene] Through fusion to the promoter region of possible trans-cis acting elements, the change in fluorescence is measured and allows for tracking into transcriptional activity.
[src:high-throughput-screening/reporter-gene] This provides useful information into understanding the pathways these elements are involved in and its regulatory uses for cell development and growth.
[src:high-throughput-screening/reporter-gene] Immune responses are also a commonly used application of reporter genes and have benefited greatly through their use.
[src:high-throughput-screening/reporter-gene] They have allowed for further understanding in cell proliferation and differentiation into B-cells and T-cells during immune responses and have contributed to understanding activation through tracking cytokine signaling pathways.
[src:high-throughput-screening/reporter-gene] The development of reporter cell lines have also emerged with the discovery and use of reporter genes.
[src:high-throughput-screening/reporter-gene] The cell lines are labelled with reporter genes to allow for fluorescent detection to help with identification into proteins used in cellular pathways and identification into protein localization.
[src:high-throughput-screening/reporter-gene] This has allowed for a simple way to study protein progression that doesn't permit further experimentation for introduction and fusion of a reporter gene as the reporter gene is already present in the cell line.
[src:high-throughput-screening/reporter-gene] A more complex use of reporter genes on a large scale is in two-hybrid screening, which aims to identify proteins that natively interact with one another *in vivo*.
[src:high-throughput-screening/reporter-gene] The yeast two-hybrid (Y2H) system, developed in the late 1980s and early 1990s, was an immense advancement in the use of reporter genes to study protein-protein interactions *in vivo*.
[src:high-throughput-screening/reporter-gene] This technique takes advantage of transcription factors' modular nature, which often consists of separate DNA-binding and activation domains.
[src:high-throughput-screening/reporter-gene] By genetically fusing two proteins of interest to these domains, researchers can detect physical interactions between them through the activation of a downstream reporter gene.
[src:high-throughput-screening/reporter-gene] Due to the simple genetic nature of the Y2H system, this technique significantly increased the accessibility of protein-protein interaction studies without the requirement of protein purification or complex biochemical assays.
[src:high-throughput-screening/reporter-gene] Experimental Y2H data have played a pivotal role in building large-scale synthetic human interactomes and in dissecting mechanisms in human disease.
[src:high-throughput-screening/reporter-gene] However, there are still some limitations.
[src:high-throughput-screening/reporter-gene] Y2H sometimes detects interactions that don't occur naturally or fails to detect weak or transient interactions.
[src:high-throughput-screening/reporter-gene] Due to its artificial setting, these failures could result from the absence of key factors such as post-translational modifications or compartmentalization.
[src:high-throughput-screening/reporter-gene] Massively parallel reporter assays (MPRAs) and machine learning are newer ways to study gene regulation with reporter genes.
[src:high-throughput-screening/reporter-gene] One major use is in synthetic biology and gene therapy, where researchers can design better regulatory elements to control gene expression.
[src:high-throughput-screening/reporter-gene] For example, deep learning models trained on MPRA data have been used to optimize 5' untranslated regions (UTRs) for mRNA translation, enabling tailored designs that enhance gene-editing efficiency in the therapeutic context.
[src:high-throughput-screening/reporter-gene] This could make mRNA-based treatments more effective, as MPRAs also help identify how genetic variants affect gene expression, which is used in precision medicine and developing personalized treatments.
[src:high-throughput-screening/reporter-gene] Machine learning models trained on MPRA data can predict how different sequences impact gene activity, making it easier to design reporter genes that respond in specific ways.
[src:high-throughput-screening/reporter-gene] Combining MPRAs with next-gen sequencing also makes reporter gene experiments faster and more scalable.
[src:high-throughput-screening/reporter-gene] These advances could even improve mRNA-based vaccines and therapeutics by optimizing untranslated regions (UTRs) to boost stability and translation.
[src:high-throughput-screening/reporter-gene] For instance, modular MPRAs have uncovered context-specific regulatory sequences linked to type 2 diabetes, revealing enhancer-promoter interactions dependent on cell-specific transcription factors like HNF1.
[src:high-throughput-screening/reporter-gene] Similarly, MPRA screens of cardiac enhancer variants have pinpointed functional noncoding sequences influencing QT interval variability, directly linking genetic variation to disease-associated gene dysregulation.
[src:high-throughput-screening/z-factor] The **Z-factor** is a measure of statistical effect size.
[src:high-throughput-screening/z-factor] It has been proposed for use in high-throughput screening (HTS), where it is also known as Z-prime, to judge whether the response in a particular assay is large enough to warrant further attention.
[src:high-throughput-screening/z-factor] In HTS, experimenters often compare a large number (hundreds of thousands to tens of millions) of single measurements of unknown samples to positive and negative control samples.
[src:high-throughput-screening/z-factor] The particular choice of experimental conditions and measurements is called an assay.
[src:high-throughput-screening/z-factor] Large screens are expensive in time and resources.
[src:high-throughput-screening/z-factor] Therefore, prior to starting a large screen, smaller test (or pilot) screens are used to assess the quality of an assay, in an attempt to predict if it would be useful in a high-throughput setting.
[src:high-throughput-screening/z-factor] The Z-factor is an attempt to quantify the suitability of a particular assay for use in a full-scale HTS.
[src:high-throughput-screening/z-factor] The Z-factor is defined in terms of four parameters: the means ( $\mu$ ) and standard deviations ( $\sigma$ ) of samples (s) and controls (c).
[src:high-throughput-screening/z-factor] The Z'-factor (Z-prime factor) is defined in terms of four parameters: the means ( $\mu$ ) and standard deviations ( $\sigma$ ) of both the positive (p) and negative (n) controls ( $\mu _{p}$ , $\sigma _{p}$ , and $\mu _{n}$ , $\sigma _{n}$ ).
[src:high-throughput-screening/z-factor] The Z'-factor is a characteristic parameter of the assay itself, without intervention of samples.
[src:high-throughput-screening/z-factor] The Z-factor defines a characteristic parameter of the capability of hit identification for each given assay.
[src:high-throughput-screening/z-factor] The following categorization of HTS assay quality by the value of the Z-Factor is a modification of Table 1 shown in Zhang *et al.* (1999); note that the Z-factor cannot exceed one.
[src:high-throughput-screening/z-factor] Note that by the standards of many types of experiments, a zero Z-factor would suggest a large effect size, rather than a borderline useless result as suggested above.
[src:high-throughput-screening/z-factor] For example, if σp=σn=1, then μp=6 and μn=0 gives a zero Z-factor.
[src:high-throughput-screening/z-factor] But for normally-distributed data with these parameters, the probability that the positive control value would be less than the negative control value is less than 1 in 105.
[src:high-throughput-screening/z-factor] Extreme conservatism is used in high throughput screening due to the large number of tests performed.
[src:high-throughput-screening/z-factor] The constant factor 3 in the definition of the Z-factor is motivated by the normal distribution, for which more than 99% of values occur within three times standard deviations of the mean.
[src:high-throughput-screening/z-factor] If the data follow a strongly non-normal distribution, the reference points (e.g. the meaning of a negative value) may be misleading.
[src:high-throughput-screening/z-factor] Another issue is that the usual estimates of the mean and standard deviation are not robust; accordingly many users in the high-throughput screening community prefer the "Robust Z-prime" which substitutes the median for the mean and the median absolute deviation for the standard deviation.
[src:high-throughput-screening/z-factor] Extreme values (outliers) in either the positive or negative controls can adversely affect the Z-factor, potentially leading to an apparently unfavorable Z-factor even when the assay would perform well in actual screening .
[src:high-throughput-screening/z-factor] In addition, the application of the single Z-factor-based criterion to two or more positive controls with different strengths in the same assay will lead to misleading results .
[src:high-throughput-screening/z-factor] The absolute sign in the Z-factor makes it inconvenient to derive the statistical inference of Z-factor mathematically.
[src:high-throughput-screening/z-factor] A recently proposed statistical parameter, strictly standardized mean difference (SSMD), can address these issues.
[src:high-throughput-screening/z-factor] One estimate of SSMD is robust to outliers.
